vectorData.altText: 6. Identify the class of tissue. Be specific.
That’s right! Articular cartilage is hyaline cartilage that lacks a perichondrium.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Hyaline cartilage is the most common and weakest cartilage. Its ECM is largely packed with collagen type II fibrils, forming a firm gel-like ground substance.
Hyaline cartilage forms tracheal rings, laryngeal, nasal, costal, articular* cartilages, much of the fetal and immature skeleton, epiphyseal (growth) plates. 
It functions to resist compression; provides tough, flexible support; reduces friction between bony surfaces in articulations.
*all hyaline cartilage structures are surrounded by perichondrium except articular cartilage; this makes sense: the vessels and nerves of the perichondrium would be damaged by the frictional forces applied as articular surfaces move relative to each other.
from Gr. hyalos = glassy; based on the appearance of fresh cartilage
Once again, the body’s design is impeccable!
